text:
6 months ago i was raped. 
if you wpuldve asked me then if i thought it was my fault i would have told you yes. if you ask me now if i think it's my fault, the answer is still yes. was i making the right decisions, no. did i get myself into a situation i couldn't get out of, absolutely. i'm not posting this for sympathy, i'm posting this to share my story. every month goes by, and i get stronger. i have been hospitalized 3 times since then for mental health issues. i used to let it ruin me, i did. i don't now. it's part of me and it's something i can't change. my point of sharing this story with you is that you are better than your circumstances. i've become one of the strongest people i know. and you can be just as strong. don't let a situation or a circumstance beat you down. you are so much better than that. don't forget it. 
happy thanksgiving 
#metoo

at the back of my mind 
hoping, praying and pleading, 
that you'll come back to me
but i guess, it's only wishful thinking 
and there's no way of getting back to who we were 
so maybe i'll take all the good stuff, 
and leave the broken promises you one made-
behind

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
follow my movement. | happy thanksgiving everyone! i am thankful for my friends, my family, to be living in los angeles pursuing my dreams,  for community and i am thankful for being a latina living in a time where our voice matters and we can use social platforms for expansion and change. i have never heard so many conversations around difficult subjects like #metoo, race, #equalpay, consciousness and many others brought to surface by powerful people to create movements, compassion and awareness. 
being a proud latina, i am passionate about having my culture be authentically represented in entertainment. like it or not we learn a great deal from the things we watch on tv and film ‚Ä¶ what better way to tackle this then to bring us all together so we can rise together and create enriching stories of our culture and people‚Ä¶ i bring you the @latinxdatabase - a community of latinx actors, writers, directors to expand diversity on and behind the camera. 
please follow my page to enrich your knowledge of the incredible latinx talent we have waiting to be discovered and supported. together we can make sure the entertainment we see and and the people behind making it happen look like the world we live in - full of color!

@latinxdatabase

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

lavender is so good for the littles too! i use a drop in hudson‚Äôs bath and he goes right to snooze town afterwards! i also like to spray his dockatot, wubbanubs, and crib sheets!

"kelly reminds me of stories about creepy neighbors, or the weird and uncomfortable social studies teacher at my middle school. his identity preceded him. as fans, we grew up enjoying his music. then, as black girls in #chicago, we grew up hearing about the sexual assault accusations against him. for me, something changed the older i got. if the culture leads our modes of behavior, then our behavior (my behavior) began operating through willful ignorance. i grew up very much loving his music and so i tried to rationalize my enjoyment of it. others around me did too. meaning, we would pretend we didn‚Äôt understand what allegedly went on to live in the bliss of our naivet√©."
.
"but more than anything, i believe black chicago‚Äôs continued acceptance of kelly is not unlike the pack mentality responses to ‚Äú#rapeculture‚Äù around the world. we become numb to the absurdities of our reality for the sake of entertainment. nearly every young black woman growing up in and around the city has heeded a warning about a non-famous, non-wealthy person in our community after hearing rumors through the grapevine. young women change their behavior to try and stay alive, as if it is their actions or their clothing or their makeup which breeds predatory behavior. where is the outrage? for if we actually believed predatory behavior was wrong truly, we wouldn‚Äôt actively keep secrets in the dark for generations or pass stories along as funny anecdotes. we would teach young people boundaries and the importance of #consent. our current culture of violence says girls and women are responsible for the things that happen to them. you read the stories and heard the rumors and knew ‚Äúthe deal,‚Äù they say. what happens next is a reflection of you."
.

text:
survivaversary 2018 - one year since surviving the worst decision of my life. 
november 22nd, 2017 i spent the day in the hospital, suffering from suicidal ideations and trauma, and had tried to commit suicide. 
in the year since, i have grown more than i thought possible, thanks mostly to intensive therapy and a fantastic support group. 
today is a day of celebration for me, because it did get better. i have an incredible job, am in school and thriving, with good friends and a dream relationship. i pushed through the worst time of my life to reach the best, and while it's not perfect, it is so much better, and so good. i could not have even conceived of this future for myself last year.
if you are in this kind of dark place, please take this as hope. it does get better. you are worthy of help. please do what you can to help yourself, because you deserve it. 
i am so lucky to see today, and i am so grateful.

text:
there are many different experiences we will have over thanksgiving - some of us will have lots of food, some of us will struggle to have enough. some will be surrounded by people and some will be alone or with just one other person. for many, it‚Äôs an important time of coming together with family. this day also gives us a chance to look at and change stories we have about our families and ourselves. thanksgiving is based on myths that hide and erase‚Äã the genocide that the united states is founded upon. what would it mean to tell a different story; an honest story? to my white friends on thanksgiving: will you commit to having bold conversations about race and the true history of this day with other white folks around your holiday dinner table? when we don‚Äôt engage, silence is the same as our approval, which is the same as oppression. please visit @lilnativeboy for their article in paper magazine called thanksgiving: the national day of mourning. and surj (showing up for racial justice) has put together a toolkit for conversations with your family. check it out at boldconversations.org - and visit @mattmcgorry for some helpful videos. and there‚Äôs a hotline ‚Äî rather than offering advice on whether you‚Äôve undercooked a turkey and potentially poisoned your family, surj‚Äôs hotline offers a way to get some quick talking points to help you stay in tough conversations with family members, whether about thanksgiving, immigration, #metoo, or more. just text sos to 82623 in order to get started!
________

text:
rp artist @laura_salafia  day four of folktale week is ghost. in honor of all of the animals that perished in the recent devastating california wildfires, i illustrated the spirits of the woodland creatures who perished in the fire. i have been deeply saddened by not only the staggering loss of human lives, homes and businesses, but how heartbreaking and sickening it is to loose such an abundance of animals, trees, plants and insects. the loss of their natural habitat and to the beauty of the natural spaces that were destroyed is hard to swallow. my heart goes out to everyone affected by the california wildfires. i hope the communities and natural habitats can find ways to recover. 
what's folktale week?
folktale week is a drawing challenge hosted by amazing illustrators. the goal is to make one illustration per day during a week (12-18 november). the illustrations have to be based on predifined themes. the themes are: forest, magic, witch, ghost, insect, mirror, and animal. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî

text:
why don‚Äôt millennials have more sex? maybe we‚Äôre just too stresseddami olonisakin

there‚Äôs a popular misconception that millennials are lazy, entitled and whiners. we‚Äôre also told that we‚Äôre nothing more than a sex-obsessed generation who are constantly at it like rabbits. but although we‚Äôre more progressive than generations before us in terms of being sex-positive, we¬†aren‚Äôt having as much sex¬†as many would like to believe, because of stress and anxiety.

in a¬†new survey¬†of just over 2,000 people for the bbc, 45% of adults said they had experienced negative impact on their sex life due to stress; 32% of people said their physical health was a factor; while 26% named mental health issues as the cause. you might think this just affects older people, but it follows other studies, such as¬†a 2015 study by dr jean twenge, which found millennials were having less sex, with fewer sexual partners, in comparison with our parents‚Äô generation when they were our age. and¬†another survey, from september, found 25% of couples in their 30s have a ‚Äúsexless‚Äù relationship ‚Äì but 77% of those aged 30 to 34 say their partner would like to have more sex.

my usual life, o male up for everyone else. within relations of a.fadhion. not casually. my own personal disclaimer.

so exactly why aren‚Äôt we ripping each others clothes off like generation x and the baby boomers once did? after all, we are the ones who put up the fight to become more sexually liberated: we‚Äôre moving away from¬†slut-shaming, and talking more about what consent should look like in and outside of the bedroom. what‚Äôs more, we‚Äôve even been dubbed the hook-up generation ‚Äì perhaps just one with no one to hook up with.

the truth, for many of us, is that we‚Äôre simply stressed out and at our wits‚Äô end, with a million things on our minds that could be interfering with our libidos. we‚Äôre worried about finding a stable job, our university loan debt, moving out of our parents‚Äô homes and more. don‚Äôt let the colour aesthetic of our instagram layouts fool you ‚Äì we‚Äôre slightly freaking out and don‚Äôt really have it together.

text:
(2/5) 
second,  i am grateful for all of my experiences. when i was in grade school, i was molested by my piano teacher. i didn‚Äôt know what he was doing honestly so i let it keep happening month after month. one day i told my mom about it while waiting for my brother to finish his piano lesson. she never let me go back, and i honestly didn‚Äôt know why. when i was in college, they stole my first time. i still remember the pain, how stunned i felt, and i had no idea what to do next. there was no one to call for help; in fact, at that time i couldn‚Äôt even pinpoint the word for what happened to me. i researched online and found about this thing called plan b. i learned about std testing. i think researching saved me. sometimes, i still remember that pain, and i now know the words to label what happened, but i am proud of myself for getting through everything. i didn‚Äôt even freak out, and i can say that i feel more comfortable in my body this year. #metoo

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
@thetriibechicago has a question: are y‚Äôall still muting @rkelly this holiday season?
.
‚úçüèæ @britticisms writes: ‚Äú#rkelly and his music, perhaps more than any other contemporary figure, reflects the culture of #blackchicago. his music ties into specific types of parties here, dance styles born here...‚Äù
.
"kelly reminds me of stories about creepy neighbors, or the weird and uncomfortable social studies teacher at my middle school. his identity preceded him. as fans, we grew up enjoying his music. then, as black girls in #chicago, we grew up hearing about the sexual assault accusations against him. for me, something changed the older i got. if the culture leads our modes of behavior, then our behavior (my behavior) began operating through willful ignorance. i grew up very much loving his music and so i tried to rationalize my enjoyment of it. others around me did too. meaning, we would pretend we didn‚Äôt understand what allegedly went on to live in the bliss of our naivet√©."
.
"but more than anything, i believe black chicago‚Äôs continued acceptance of kelly is not unlike the pack mentality responses to ‚Äú#rapeculture‚Äù around the world. we become numb to the absurdities of our reality for the sake of entertainment. nearly every young black woman growing up in and around the city has heeded a warning about a non-famous, non-wealthy person in our community after hearing rumors through the grapevine. young women change their behavior to try and stay alive, as if it is their actions or their clothing or their makeup which breeds predatory behavior. where is the outrage? for if we actually believed predatory behavior was wrong truly, we wouldn‚Äôt actively keep secrets in the dark for generations or pass stories along as funny anecdotes. we would teach young people boundaries and the importance of #consent. our current culture of violence says girls and women are responsible for the things that happen to them. you read the stories and heard the rumors and knew ‚Äúthe deal,‚Äù they say. what happens next is a reflection of you."
.

.

-
if you know me, you‚Äôll know that i‚Äôm on a mission to help more women live a fully expressed life. but too many women hold back from sharing their writing with the world because:

‚ö°Ô∏è writing a book feels far too overwhelming and time-consuming.

no more!

text:
next week, the diplomatic societies debate session will be simulating unwomen to discuss modern day sexual harassment, in line with the #metoo campaign. 
the #metoo movement has been of paramount importance in bringing to light the suppressed voices of millions of women across the world who have experienced sexual harassment and discrimination. 
it‚Äôs significance has been global: throughout the world, there have been several variants of the #metoo hashtag, from the italian #quellavoltache to the norwegian #stilleforopptak and french #balancetonporc 
yet, whilst this campaign has been progressive, this opportunity for speaking up against sexual harassment remains inaccessible for a vast majority of women around the world, who live in conditions of poverty, enslavement, or oppression. 
it will be our jobs as unwomen delegates, to give a voice to the millions of silently oppressed women around the world, and work to ensure a future where this hashtag is no longer needed. 
unwomen is dedicated to achieving gender equality, dignity, and empowerment for all women. 
for more information on this debate, please visit our facebook page at www.facebook.com/rhuldiplomaticsociety (link in bio), or feel free to send us a direct message here! 
the picture above is of three young girls at school in a remote hill tribe in mae hong son district in northern thailand. photo taken by @chiraagjs 
#metoo #unwomen #genderequality #femaleempowerment #thisgirlcan #unitednations #royalholloway #surhul #politics #internationalrelations #modelunitednations

text:
sharing a big announcement! üíú
-
at the beginning of last year in a session with my mentor, i connected with a powerful vision.
i saw myself with a group of women around me, each one carrying a drop of silver liquid. one after one, each of the women stepped forward with her droplet and together they formed a beautiful, silver pool.
-
as i connected with that vision, i knew that as well as being beautiful, that silver pool was so powerful it could move mountains; that when combined, the magic that each of these women carried was potent enough to be world-changing.
-
so, i had a vision. but i wasn't at all sure how it would manifest. -
then earlier this eye, when i was meeting with my publisher, se√°n patrick of @thatguyshouse, in london to discuss my latest book, unbound, he asked me a question:
what if i started a publishing imprint specifically to release books by and for unbound women?
-
immediately i knew this was what i meant to do. (you know when something feels so right?)
-
and so, today, i'm beyond excited to share the launch of @theunboundpress with you: a soul-led publishing imprint committed to working with female authors whose writing activates a feeling of deep connection and transformation in others.
-
so many of the women i connect with have an important message to share with the world. but often they hold back from writing a book because they don't know where to start and doubt whether there are enough people who would want to read what they have to share.
no more.
-
the time for holding back has passed. movements such as #metoo have shown us the power of women coming together and sharing their stories. and if there‚Äôs one thing i‚Äôm certain of, it‚Äôs that in these tumultuous and transformational times, the world needs your magic. -
the unbound press has been created as a space where women can be part of a community of authors, all bringing their unique medicine to the world.
-
we're currently in talks wth our first authors and if you're interested in finding out more about the unbound press, comment below or send me a message and i'll give you some more details.
-
and make sure you follow @theunboundpress to be part of the magic!

text:
when i was in 7th standard i went to a mall to attend a conference with my dad. his office was behind the mall and he told me to wait there for about an hour till he comes back. while i was standing there a guy was continually staring at me and suddenly came near and stood beside me. he started talking to me and suddenly he tried to show me something on his phone. it was porn. he started talking about porn. i got scared and ran away from there but he followed me everywhere. i hid in the washroom, and, to my surprise, he followed me there also, groped me from the back, tried to touch my private body parts. fortunately, somebody came and he left. i locked myself in the bathroom until my father came.

i was traumatised, shaken, and tears were rolling out of my eyes, but i couldn‚Äôt share the incident with my dad. i got sick for a week. still today i haven‚Äôt told my parents about the incident but with the onset of the #metoo movement, i finally gathered the courage to share it.

text:
introducing our next #akintakeover @sveavikander. svea vikander is a multimedia journalist whose work addresses areas of female bodily autonomy and creative self-expression. she produces and co-hosts art crush (kalx90.7 fm), a radio show that brings the audience into the intimacy of artists‚Äô studios, where she interviews them about their lives, struggles, and triumphs. she is also a freelance writer and the performance art critic at theatrius.
svea holds an ma in clinical mental health counseling and has had a small private practice for the past decade. in 2014, her commitment to women‚Äôs rights led her to provide a year of therapy to at-risk families at the homeless prenatal program in san francisco. more recently, she has brought her expertise in neurodiversity to provide in-person and remote counseling to creative people around the world. 
svea was a pioneer of the #metoo movement in canada: in 2016, she published 30 pieces of deeply vulnerable writing about her experiences in a national news outlet. she is committed to working toward a world in which we can all find and share our stories. svea was recently honored by the university of toronto for her body of work, receiving the young alumna of influence award from university college in 2018. 
svea lives in berkeley and online at twitter (@sveavikander) and instagram (@sveavikander). her website is sveavikander.com

text:
people have hurt me all my life. mentally and physically. 
my ex-stepbrother raped me. my father just left us. my classmates bullied me every day and they pushed me until i fell down. my ex punched me in my face.
there's one thing i never ever told anyone yet. the worst thing and part of my nightmares. the day my ex-stepbrother almost killed me because i wanted to defend myself only once.
i was 8 years old. i was alone with him so i knew he will rape me again. and this day i wanted to defend myself. he came into my room and grabbed my shoulders. i kicked him in his balls and began to run. i just wanted to get downstairs and out of the house. but he was so much faster than me. he caught me and grabbed my ponytail. and then he smashed my head on the corner of the coffee table. twice. i heard my head crack, the most horrible sound i've ever heard. next thing i can remember is waking up in hospital. my mom was sitting there with him. he told her it was an accident, that i fell while we were playing catch. 
and i never told her the truth, she still thinks it was an accident. i never told anyone about it, this is the first and last time. i was lucky he didn't hit my head a third time because that might have killed me. a small piece of my skull broke off, you can't see it but you can feel it on my forehead. 
i never tried to defend myself ever again. i was even more afraid of him. and he's the reason why i'm always scared of men when i meet them for the first time.
it feels so good to tell you my secret, this is the only thing i've never told anyone. really, thank you for reading this.
.
.

lol thos story remind me of primary. so you know kiss chase? well i was either good at it or terrible. i am too fast so i could always be able to catch girls. they'd ask to he let go and let off the cool, i'd always oblige. in reverse o couldn't ever be caught so girls would invariably give up going after me, i loved the running stopping and letting them almost touch me and then darting off on a new direction as they skidded to a halt somewhere i had never been.

our partner organization the internet democracy project (idp) organized a one-of-a-kind gathering of female activists " #mytrollourtroll" in new delhi. the sessions at this closed door event explored the mobile phone and the internet as new battlegrounds in the fight against patriarchy and forms of discrimination used against women. the victims of online abuse shared their stories and strategies of dealing with the perpetrators on platforms like facebook and twitter.

text:
‚Ä¢you're not alone dear @yourlocalrosa @natasyacn #kitaagni‚Ä¢

kami #aliansimahasiswaupstegal #beranibicara sebagai kelompok pendukung #metoo #breakthesilence untuk me- #lawankekerasanseksual berusaha mendeteksi bagaimana ketidakadilan gender terjadi di lingkungan terdekat, khususnya kampus.

kami mempelajari pola-pola kekerasan seksual di kampus dan memiliki beberapa catatan tentangnya.

pertama, setiap terjadi kasus kekerasan seksual seperti pelecehan seksual oleh dosen, senior, atau teman seangkatan, biasanya cerita tentang kasus tersebut hanya menjadi kabar yang terbang terbawa angin dari mulut ke mulut.

kasus-kasus seperti pelecehan dan diskriminasi seksual tidak ditindaklanjuti karena pertama, tidak ada tempat yang aman untuk bercerita dan melaporkan kasus-kasus kekerasan seksual.

kedua, tidak ada mekanisme sistem pelaporan dan sanksi yag jelas apabila peraturan dilanggar, dan ketiga, tidak ada pendokumentasian kasus-kasus kekerasan seksual yang terjadi.

akibatnya, kasus-kasus kekerasan seksual di lingkungan kampus menjadi sekadar rahasia umum dan tabu untuk dibicarakan karena menyangkut nama baik kampus.

nama baik kampus dipertaruhkan apabila terjadi kasus kekerasan seksual; pihak kampus merasa tercoreng apabila dicitrakan gagal dalam melindungi mahasiswa padahal mereka bahkan tidak berusaha melindungi mereka.

penyangkalan atas terjadinya kekerasan seksual di lingkungan kampus justru melanggengkan kekerasan tersebut dan nama baik kampus justru lebih tercoreng apabila kampus justru tidak menindak pelaku dengan serius, serta tidak memperbaiki sistem untuk menciptakan ruang aman bebas kekerasan dan diskriminasi bagi seluruh warga.

penyangkalan ini dilakukan secara sistematis, tercermin dari bagaimana pihak-pihak terkait meminta korban untuk bungkam, dan meminta korban menyelesaikan kasus-kasus dengan asas kekeluargaan.

jika kampus ingin mencitrakan sebagai tepat yang aman dan bebas dari kekerasan seksual, penyangkalan demi nama baik sudah membuktikan kampus telah gagal segagal-gagalnya dalam melindungi korban.

syuting housefull 4 selesai, kriti sanon ungkap dirinya kerja bareng akshay kumar üòâ

kriti sanon mengungkapkan bagaimana perasaannya bekerja dengan akshay kumar di 'housefull 4'. saat tim 'housefull 4' menyelesaikan serangkaian jadwal syuting mereka, para pemain di media sosial masing-masing memposting foto yang sama. kriti sanon yang juga merupakan salah satu dari tiga wanita terkemuka di housefull 4 menyatakan bagaimana perasaannya bekerja dengan akshay kumar.

berbagi gambar monokrom dengan akshay kumar, dia menulis, "dilliwaalas dengan senyumannya yang kenyal !!" senang sekali bekerja dengan anda, tuan !! terima kasih karena anda begitu luar biasa, begitu dingin, lucu, dan sangat lucu! ü§ó‚ù§Ô∏è @akshaykumar dorongan konstan anda untuk menambahkan sesuatu yang baru ke layar agar lebih baik memberi inspirasi! üôå "

sementara itu, pemeran film housefull 4 lainnya termasuk riteish deshmukh, bobby deol, kriti kharbanda dan pooja hegde juga memposting sesuai perasaan mereka sendiri diakun media sosial masing-masing.

pembuat film farhad samji mengambil alih 
kendali film setelah mantan sutradara housefull 4, sajid khan mengundurkan diri setelah tuduhan #metoo.

housefull 4 dijadwalkan untuk rilis tahun depan pada kesempatan diwali 2019. üòâ

.

text:
he adored the sparkle of her eyes,
only to make them trickle with tears and silent cries.

he craved to kiss those red lips,
bruised, with the same color as they dripped.

he once ran his fingers fondly through those thick tresses,
only to clench them firmly and strike her crown against the wall, until she turned senseless.

whenever they met, he was intrigued that her cheeks blushed,
only to smack it blue-black as the blood gushed.

he was the luckiest to put a ring on that finger,
only to contort it until she shrieked and prayed for justice in this gradual murder.
___________________________________________

3/3 that is a wrap of ngtby. we were filming in a black box studio with minimal set design representing a location with different trailers where the characters were living. in that aspect, it was quite similar to dogville. however, our set was more minimalistic and the lighting was the key to set time of the day, emotions or abstract moments. this, along the fact we had to film more than 50 minutes in 4 days, made the shoot super intense and challenging.

thank you again to my amazing camera and lighting people. you are stars! :d

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in 2014, steve bannon ‚Äì then executive chairman of the ‚Äúalt-right‚Äù news network breitbart ‚Äì was christopher wylie‚Äôs boss. and robert mercer, the secretive us hedge-fund billionaire and republican donor, was cambridge analytica‚Äôs investor. and the idea they bought into was to bring big data and social media to an established military methodology ‚Äì ‚Äúinformation operations‚Äù ‚Äì then turn it on the us electorate.

cambridge analytica‚Äôs parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - it‚Äôs insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? it‚Äôs like nixon on steroids.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

that‚Äôs what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him ‚Äúwe can take it.‚Äù no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but it‚Äôs a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then it‚Äôs easy to come along for the ride. there‚Äôs no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. they‚Äôre both just characters on the television.

that‚Äôs what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. it‚Äôs not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. it‚Äôs that we‚Äôve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text: #yellowheartsquad tonight i am so #thankful because i was given the chance to answer very diverse & informative questions ranging from creating a show, disability in entertainment, music, charity, and lastly the #metoo movement. some of the things i had to say took time, and i was very nervous to address certain elements of the questions. but i think it‚Äôs important to confront those fears and be honest in every response - which i was. i‚Äôve been waiting for this article to be online, and the fact that it went live the night before #thanksgiving makes it even more special. i‚Äôm #grateful for every opportunity i have to share my story in different facets to a variety of audiences. shout-out to @mightywell_ for the great picc line cover featured in the photo! it has kept my picc safe, and comfortable since having it placed weeks ago. to read @occhimagazine please check out my news & media story highlights and swipe up on the article! üíõ please share it so that others can have a chance to understand the perspective of hollywood that i‚Äôve come to know. most importantly, in regards to metoo, no one should ever have to deal with sexual harassment in any business or workplace - regardless of gender. i am here for you, i stand by you, and i defend you. always. #cysticfibrosis #cf #transplant #hope

text: there are only a handful of films so far this year that have truly shaken me to the bone: annihilation, suspiria, roma, green book, boy erased and now widows. outstanding across the board - this film manages to expertly weave gender, race, class, morality, survival, female empowerment, reverberations of #metoo, what it means to be human and a citizen of this country into one epic crime-heist-drama-thriller! i am in awe of every single person associated with this film. if this sounds hyperbolic to you, i implore you to watch it and immerse yourself in steve mcqueen‚Äôs bravura filmmaking and his outstanding ensemble led by the always awe-inspiring viola davis. #widows #stevemcqueen #violadavis #gillianflynn #elizabethdebicki #michellerodriguez #cynthiaerivo

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

2015: courage - the year i left my abusive relationship, travelled to nashville solo and found inner freedom for the first time in my life 
2016: faith - the year i survived an assault, self-sabatoging behaviour, an attempted suicide and was saved by the grace of god 
2017: perseverance - the year i shared my story for the first time, lost weight, gained weight, suffered extreme ptsd and anxiety and signed on with my agency @theselfpublishingagency to write this book
2018: trust - the year i moved to the unknown, started a new job, said goodbye, wrote hard chapters, experienced multiple deaths, had a massive breakdown, learned to stop trusting the wrong people, learned to start trusting the right people and my intuition, went back to nashville and reconnected with the person i lost 3 years ago, and found that softness and light again.
2019: determination, strength, love, growth, breath, endless possibilities and more. this year is going to be beautiful because it will be the year i stand in my truth, stop making excuses, finish and launch my book and use what has been beautifully gifted to me to help others find their light #quote

text:
the purpose of the love necklace one-for-one giving campaign is to build a community connection through sharing love by purchasing a love necklace so that a woman receiving care at a women's shelter can receive a necklace as a symbol, reminding her that she is loved as well.  once you purchase a necklace, you have the opportunity to choose which shelter will receive it.  the shelters served through this campaign include genesis women's shelter & support in dallas, safe in austin, new orleans women & children's shelter, hope haven in san pedro, belize, and haven house in belize city.

click here to participate and learn more about the campaign: http://www.mpulsestudio.com/the-love-necklace-campaign/‚ù§Ô∏è #love .

text:
tw- sexual assault, but if you can, please read.

the abuse of underage girls must stop.
no girl of any age should have to say #metoo. let alone a young girl with theater aspirations, an innocent child.
the sak channels were a favorite of mine in early middle school-i even ran a fan account. i loved theater and acting back then. having been constantly rejected from school plays, not being accepted by the theater community at my school. i wanted to be like the girls on the saks. i almost auditioned, until i realized that putting myself out there and submitting a video of myself as a "audition tape", even with an innocuous skit, could be dangerous.
and turns out, i was right.
recently, creator of the sak enterprise ian rylett was arrested on molestation charges. following the charges, the girls that id looked up to were put through abuse and molested for the entertainment of others. 
this is a sick world we live in. sexual abuse is never ok. no young girl should ever be able to day #metoo. thinking of what couldve happened to me if id submitted that tape and possibly been accepted... it is beyond what i could dream. even today, a catcall or inappropriate encounter on the street scares me to death. 
men that abuse young girls deserve nothing. many may say the girls were "asking for it" by putting themselves out there, but not many would suspect child grooming on a well established channel with millions of subscribers claiming to be parent moderated.
please. if you are ever a victim of manipulation, sexual assault by a person "in power", please talk to someone. its easier said than done, i know. but just know- if your reading this and you have experienced this, i love and believe you.

#sakschannel

text:
her
.
do you remember her wild spirit 
before someone shut her down for being outspoken
before someone told her she talks too much
before someone questioned her every decision
.
do you remember her gracious heart
before someone stepped on it
before someone stole it's innocence and threw away the key
before someone broke it in to million pieces while she was trying to keep it all together
.
do you remember her willingness and good nature 
before someone belittled her efforts
before someone said she was¬† overthinking too much
before someome showed her that trusting others was a dangerous road
.
do you remember her hopeful spirit
before someone trampled on it
before someone erased her pleasant optimism
before someone crushed her hopes and dreams
.
because if you don't remember her you will do unto others what others have done to her
.
you will show her no mercy as you pummel her in to the ground 
until she no longer comes up for air because she concludes it doesn't matter
because she doesn't belong and doesn't want to belong to a place or a planet that such awful "someones" inhabit
.
so whatever you do... remember her
.
rainedrops 2018 .
.
.
.

text:
this stage of life. it‚Äôs hard, you guys.

i‚Äôm talking right now to you moms who are in your late 20's to mid 30‚Äôs. you have kids. likely two, three, maybe four of them. they probably range in age from newborns to  7 or 10 year-olds. (give or take a few, on all of the above mentioned stats). in this stage of life, you are dealing with exhaustion. mental, physical, and emotional.

in this stage of life, you are dealing with teething. with ear infections. with stomach viruses. you are juggling nap schedules, and feeding schedules and soccer, dance, or cheer schedules. a million balls you are juggling, and you probably feel like you are dropping most of them.

in this stage of life, you are dealing with guilt. guilt over having a career, and not spending enough time with your kids, or guilt over staying home with your kids, and not doing enough to contribute financially. guilt over being too harsh with your kids. too lenient. guilt that your house is clean, but your kids were ignored, or guilt that you enjoyed your children all day, and now your husband is coming home to filth. guilt.

in this stage of life, you are bombarded daily with a whole host of decisions. some of them life-changing, some of them not. none of them with clear cut answers. do i vaccinate my kids? do i not? do i send them to public school? homeschool? charter school? do i continue to breastfeed? do i blow the budget so that i can buy all organic? do i force my child to apologize, even though the apology will be insincere? you don‚Äôt know the answers to anything, but you feel constant pressure to figure out everything.

this stage of life is less and less about watching your friends get married and have babies, and more and more about standing by and witnessing your friends struggle in their marriage, and even get divorced. it‚Äôs a stage where you‚Äôve got to put in the time and the effort and the work and the energy to make sure your own marriage stays healthy. and that‚Äôs good, but it‚Äôs hard, too. at this point, you or someone you know has experienced infertility. miscarriages. loss of a child.

it‚Äôs a stage where you are buying houses, selling houses, remodeling houses, packing up houses. and then

‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî-
i started cutting myself when i was 13 years old,off and on for years.
my  first attempt at suicide was  with pills and i was 15 
my second attempt at suicide was when i was 22, i slit my wrist and  a friend had to suture the wound closed because it wouldn‚Äôt stop bleeding. 
my 3rd attempt, 26 years old. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
self mutilation eased the mental pain, and took my mind off the physical pain i endured day in and day out.the suicide attempts were a result of being told over and over and over again how terrible a person i was, how l lucky i was to be alive because it was by ‚Äútheir‚Äù good graces i was. i woke up each day wondering how i could stay out of trouble so i wouldn‚Äôt be yelled at, put down or punished, mixed in with sexual abuse, i was pushed to my breaking point constantly.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
through all of this, all i wanted was simply to be loved and not lied to. at 26 years old, all i want is to to be loved and not lied to.  my eyes have been opened this year to so many truths about the people around me and myself as a person , and it was so agonizing for me to handle that i nearly closed my eyes myself for good. ‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
the year is nearly over and i stand tall, i stand with my instincts honed and sharp, i am aware of who is loyal, and who is lying. i stand strong, i stand to live. my eyes are wide open and i don‚Äôt intend on closing them anytime soon.
‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî‚Äî
if you are struggling, i urge you to keep those eyes open, there is someone to live for and that person is you.

and to those out there, lying, disrespecting, belittling, manipulating, and being all around jack asses.... i am coming for you. 
#suicideawareness #metoo #loyalty #healwithlove #respect #iknowwhatyoudidtome #towriteloveonherarms

text:
a little twisted?

come sit next to me at the table

because there are plenty of people who don‚Äôt get your humor
and the ones who do but pretend it‚Äôs not funny
those of us who chuckle at the wrong time
or find an innuendo in the strangest of places-
we see the world a little bit different 
we need to stick together. 
so tomorrow, if you find yourself chuckling (or trying not to) think of the rest of us a lot like you- and embrace that shit.  it makes dinner that much more fun üíö

text: the last few weeks have been very heavy in the media; these events have brought about a resurgence to the #metoo movement and awakened an anger in many of us. if there is any silver lining from these recent events it is the advocacy and rage we are seeing from women, female identifying individuals, & our allies. rape culture is defined as ‚Äúa society or environment whose prevailing social attitudes have the effect of normalizing or trivializing sexual assault and abuse.‚Äù we‚Äôd like to think we have made major progress, but we have not, & it is up to us to use this rage and turn it into creating change. studies have shown that increased education and awareness is the first key to prevention, so before you decide to discredit a victim because of your own discomfort, educate yourself: 1 in 3 women, and 1 in 6 men will be sexually assaulted in their lifetime; in 99% of cases of sexual assault, the perpetrator is male (regardless of the victims gender); only 2-5% of rape claims are false reports! as a survivor, this is something that i am very passionate about, but also something that i seek to educate others on. and while it may be uncomfortable to hear stories about sexual assault and rape, it is one of the most violating, & horrific experiences an individual can have. regardless of whether or not you have a personal connection to this, it is all our jobs to reduce the stigma & shame surrounding survivors of sexual assault. you can easily do this by watching your own language and how you handle these stories, as well as by calling out others when they perpetuate rape culture, & offering support to survivors. if you‚Äôre not angry you‚Äôre clearly not listening. if you have a voice, it is your duty to use it. this is not about man-hating; we need to hold our boys accountable for their actions, & as women we need to not feed into toxic masculinity. we have the right to be both sexual, & serious; how we present ourselves is never indicative of the quality of our hearts and our minds, & no one is ever ‚Äúasking for it‚Äù. no always means no, & only yes means yes. and the only thing we‚Äôre saying yes to right now is our ability to feel safe & at home in our own bodies.
name: Avaüïä

text: acknowledge your pain. talk about it. cry through it. but never let it define you, and never let it control you. do you know the kind of pain i am talking about? the kind that emotionally exhausts you to think/talk about, the kind that brings you to tears, the kind you would rather just store deep down in your ‚Äúpain box‚Äù and never talk about again. why would i say acknowledge this awful pain then? because if brought to the surface it can bring true healing. don‚Äôt let it bottle up inside you for years like i did. it almost destroyed me. don‚Äôt let it make you cold. & don‚Äôt let it dim the light you could be bringing to others. i have found that just by talking about it out loud (especially to god) brings healing. it‚Äôs taken me years of bottling emotions and past traumas to realize i haven‚Äôt fully let them go. but in order to heal i must open that pain box, cry, forgive others, forgive myself, talk to god about it alot, talk to those i trust, and find that healing. i know it‚Äôs not an overnight thing. it takes weeks, months, and sometimes years. but tonight, i am asking you to also make that small step of acknowledging the pain you feel/felt. we have become so good at wearing a mask that the mask is all we ever seem to wear. that‚Äôs a great way to lose our identity. i am realizing more and more that bringing pain into the light is where healing takes place. so, yesterday i chose to acknowledge the pain and trauma, with my husband. and today i am choosing to remember the good memories, the happy times‚Ä¶ and yes, even the pain ‚Äì what i like to think of as my little blessings in disguise. ¬†i am not denying my ‚Äúpain box‚Äù, but i am saying that even in the pain i have grasped how to find joy . life will always bring new trials, new pains, new hardships. but through that i have learned how to find true happiness and thankfulness. thankfulness for how god has been able to use this pain to reach others. the closer i get to god the more i see him testing my faith. and the more he tests my faith the more i grow. ¬†i rest tonight on this verse ‚Äúcount it all joy, my brothers,¬†when you meet trials¬†of various kinds,for you know that¬†the testing of your faith¬†produces steadfastness‚Äù ‚¨áÔ∏è

text:
what if this was your story? your experience? how do you think it would it affect your life? your future relationships? your current relationships? asking questions, showing support and empathizing with assault victims is what we should be doing. not turning our heads and shaming them.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
this was my experience. part of my story. and it happened in elementary school. this boy still haunts me and i remember the incident like it was yesterday. i certainly didn‚Äôt deserve it. and his actions were way beyond the crazy things kids do. it‚Äôs sick and fucked up. what are we doing to avoid this behavior? how are we raising our children so they know this is wrong? all i know is that the lesson starts at home and it starts from day one. something was clearly missing for this boy. i always had hoped he didn‚Äôt treat anyone else this way as he got older. i guess that is something i will never know.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
i started our stories matter so victims of assault, abuse, and domestic violence can be heard. having been a victim, i felt it was important to do something make change. and this project means so much to me. i also teamed up with licensed psychotherapist @cosmicchristine to help provide a safe place for people to come forward and open up. i am grateful for her support as well as her dedication to the cause.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
we are currently accepting submissions for the project. sharing your story not only can be therapeutic, but can help others with healing and break through the ignorance we see on the issue. and you can be anonymous if it makes you more comfortable. this collaborative journal will be real, raw, eye-opening, heartbreaking, and inspirational.
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä
you can learn more at ourstoriesmatter.info
‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä‚†Ä

text:
there are 500,000 homeless people throughout bulgaria.
[source: caritas bulgaria]

for people like irina, streetmercy is the difference between survival and sucumbing to freezing temperatures in the city of sofia.

mwb in bulgaria delivers 120 hot soups, six days a week to homeless people living in sofia. we also assist the homeless with accessing healthcare, and during the winter, we provide blankets, sleeping bags and warm clothes. we also share bible readings and provide prayer and personal counselling.

join us by becoming an mwb advocate by signing up to our newsletter using the hashtag #iamchanginglives in the form's comments box (link in bio). http://www.mwb.org.au/newsletter-sign-up/

you can find other inspiring stories in our facebook notes

text:
hear me too ! 
our voices and stories must be heard. 
one in three women experience violence in their lifetime, across all social status, class, race, country or age group. that‚Äôs one too many. for many of them, the #metoo moment hasn‚Äôt come yet, because speaking out can have fatal consequences, and survival is a long and complicated journey.
join us on november 22 at the assembly hall lawns for our clothes line project as we recognize the international day for the elimination of violence against women 
#hearmetoo
#endingviolenceagainstwomen
#idevaw2018

text:
üí™üèºarmbar from choking closed guard üôÖüèª‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è ‚ö†Ô∏èwarning ‚ö†Ô∏è
be careful when practicing, we are hyperextending our partners arm.

steps:
1) relieve pressure on neck
-lock your legs, lift your hips and extend your legs.
- pick an arm to attack and isolate it. (one arm under and over, grabbing their wrist. other hand reach over and across their arm to grab their elbow.) 2) create and angle
- place your foot on their hip, that is on the same side you have their wrist. (keep your hand grips tight)
- use the foot on their hip to help you lift your hips and axe kick your other leg on their shoulder blade.
- simultaniously, rotate your upper body towards the shoulder you are kicking.

3) finish
- throw the foot and leg that is on their hip over their head and clamp your legs down tight.
- keeping your hand grips and legs tightly squeezed, and lift your hips. (this is similar to a hip thrust.)
**when practicing go slow on lifting your hips**
.
.
.
.
.
.
.

text:
when i came home this evening my neighbor said, "happy thanksgiving. " he said he was having a small one tomorrow. i told him, "it's who is there, not how many." that is what i live by now. family is not always who you're born to or from. its who you choose. period. your abuser will say crap like, "i'm still your dad, sister, grandpa,¬† etc." no. you're not! you lost that right the first moment you abused me! i just didn't realize it until now. 
don't ever let them make you feel guilty or obligated. they are just trying to manipulate you. my ex told me to wait until after the holidays to leave. when i refused, he was pissed and told me i was ruining christmas for everyone. like he hadn't ruined every holiday i was ever with him. be strong. you can do this. you are worth so much more than what he says to you.

text:
when the last two years of insane, chaotic, toxic and utter bs i was pulled into comes to an official end. for every woman i know and i don‚Äôt know who has been sexually assaulted and never got any kind of justice, had no voice to speak out, was not believed or there was not enough ‚Äúevidence‚Äù or women coming forward to proceed...
holy fak today is for you. #guilty!!!
i seriously fought for my mental health and continued to push myself through this process for all of you. so many women i know and their horrible assaults were in my mind when i just wanted this to all go away. i thought of them and what they have been through, i cried for them not being believed or getting any kind of justice. i still do. i‚Äôm crying now. i wish we could live in a world where humans we trust didn‚Äôt abuse, manipulate and take advantage of other humans in their vulnerability. but we do. and the sobering truth is it‚Äôs not going to change. but finally we are living in a time where we can speak out, actually be believed, get help, properly heal, support/help others and hold perpetrators accountable for their perverted choices.
thank-you to the vpd, victim services, crown council, my family and all my beautiful friends for all your overwhelming support, especially @aj_____b who was by my side the entire time from the very beginning to the very end. i never had to ask or reach out because you just showed up every time. thank-you to @dario_sinagoga from @diazcombatsports for your sensitivity, support and empowering me back to my strongest, happiest, loving self in what was the most fragile 4 months of my healing. my heart bursts and doesn‚Äôt have any words to fully express how you helped me.
thanks to @praisevaughn and @bodybytak for inspiring me and strengthing me in body, mind and heart every week in your fun, uplifting and empowering classes.
you are all my spirit humans.
i. love. you. all. so. much. ‚ù£Ô∏è‚ù£Ô∏è‚ù£Ô∏è‚ù£Ô∏è‚ù£Ô∏è

text:
there is no soft or gentle way to say it: countless folks will be returning to, or trying to protect themselves from, toxic and/or abusive family members this holiday. many will be expected to confirm their plans for the ones still to come, and trying to do so while in a state of fear, tension or hostility. others will be 'celebrating' alone, keeping themselves safe but worried about the backlash it may cause or even the safety of other family members in attendance. others still will find themselves lost in the mind games, manipulation and cruelty of loved ones while also battling the same trickery and pain from their own mind and mental health.
.
we sincerely hope this article on coping with toxic and abusive families will not only help you feel less alone, but potentially save one's safety, sanity or even life. it's because of this severity and the hidden nature of this issue that we encourage you to share this article. you may be completely unaware of the dozens of friends you have wrestling with this, currently trembling in isolation and need of a lifeline.
.
[link in bio!!] can now be found at: beautyafterbruises.org/blog/toxicfamilyholidayguide
.
we are here. you are not alone. you can do this. and, we are so proud of you.
.

text:
from morning until night - oil/canvas - 24 x 30 inches

many of my paintings are designed to look like screen shots, like scenes from some larger narrative, as if you had walked into a darkened theatre after the film had started, or you had opened a random page in the middle of a novel and were unaware of what had happened before and what would occur later on.

the painting shows a hotel room in madrid: a rumpled bed, a young woman on a balcony looking down a narrow street. on the wall above the lamp hangs a reproduction of a painting from 1652 by diego vel√°zquez of a princess, painted at her age of two, a little girl who would not live to celebrate her 22nd birthday.

if you wanted to, you could interpret this painting in several ways. one viewer told me she thought the young woman was a prostitute. well, i suppose this could be so, but that was not my intention. i‚Äôm interested in the lives of women in general, especially women who find themselves alone, living in what is still a man‚Äôs world. 
in any case, in future posts you will see this woman again, and many of her sisters. i admire their curiosity, determination and resilience. but the scenes, like this one, will always remain ambiguous, as they should be.  thankfully, the women know themselves much better than i know them. 
there is one other thing i need to tell you, a coincidence which i did not realize until a few moments ago as i was writing this post: the young model who leans over the  balcony in this painting was a former student of mine. she was a fearless young artist and, later, a college graduate with a degree in engineering. a few years ago, one of her younger sisters discovered her body, two days dead, on the floor of her little kitchen. she was older than twenty-two, but not by much.

#metoo #fineart #contemporaryart #realistart #nightvisions #visualpoetry #oilpaintingsforsale

text:
it‚Äôs hard talking about the stuff that matters. the things we have a hard time admitting to ourselves let alone voicing out loud.
üôÖ‚Äç‚ôÄÔ∏è.
it‚Äôs easy to post pictures of pretty food, sweaty selfies, inspiring quotes about health & wellness ... like it‚Äôs all good over here friend.
üåπ.
only it‚Äôs not always coming up roses. these past six months i have been struggling hard with weight loss demons in my head. voices i thought i had buried but with some recent stresses in my life, these voices came galloping back in.
üêé.
and i was chatting to a really fit friend recently who said she struggles all the time with this fear of weighing too heavy. she must have like 15% body fat but she has these inner issues with the scale.

there's currently 209 women mps but so much more to be done, it's vital that women are represented throughout politics and that we ensure future generations have a platform. together we can make it happen.

text:
according to #tmz-‚Äúthe #hollywood chamber of commerce tells us the stars will be fixed today, and they believe the perp(s) will be caught, because the walk is lined with security cameras.

#jenniferlopez now has a strange and unlikely connection to #donald trump and #billcosby ... because her star on the hollywood walk of fame caught the attention of a vandal. 
someone used what looks like black spray paint to deface j lo's star tuesday ... near the famed intersection of hollywood and vine. it's not clear what message, if any, the tagger was trying to send.
cops took a vandalism report and will investigate the incident. the paint job's bad, but not nearly as destructive as what we've seen on the walk of fame earlier this year.

most of the vandalism has been focused on trump's star ... with george lopez unleashing a massive fake pee stream over it, plus the golden toilet incident, the infamous pickax attack and this sticky situation. it's gotten so bad, there was talk about removing the star permanently while potus is in office.
as for cosby -- after he was sentenced to 3 to 10 years in prison for sexual assault, someone scribbled the words "serial rapist." and "#metoo" on his star. fellow stars #pharellwilliams #ellendegeneres and #michaelbubble‚Äôs hollywood stars were also hit by this act of vandalism. it appears the coc was quick on the cleanup effort. at least as far as buble is concerned, the all stars have been scrubbed clean already.‚ÄùüëÄüòÆ (via @tmz_tv) #rap #hiphop #rnb #latin #pop #aka #love #onthe6 #rebirth #jlo #onthefloor #followus #followbackalways  #followforfollow #follow4follow #gainpost

text:
"panty portrait: pie" from the panty project, 6 of 51
.

fiber art, archival pigment print on museum cotton rag, 19 x 14 inches .

the panty project is an ongoing social practice project. participants, womxn and those who identify as womxn, courageously share with me their stories of experienced gendered transgressions and violent aggressions, whether cultural and/or interpersonal. participants write a word or phrase onto the panel of their selected undergarment; i hand-embroider over their mark-making and photograph them as if they have been taken off. this work addresses the inherent misogyny within our language, and the consequential "essestializing" of womxn, which reduces womxn, and those who identify as womxn, to "less than." this work is about healing and transcendence. 
womxn's long-silenced voices must be heard.
.

text:
did you know that more than 1 out of 3 girls in cameroon are married before they turn 18, but prevalence rates vary widely across regions: in the north 73% of girls marry as children, as opposed to 13% in the littoral province.  lack of education is strongly linked to the prevalence of child marriage: 79% of women aged 20-24 with no education and 45% with primary education were married by 18, compared to 13% of women with at least secondary schooling.
please support caepa cameroon by following us on instagram and help share our story, as we continue to empower girls and women through education, healthcare, and resources needed to become independent, self-sufficient, and self-sustainable!

text:
lance mason, an ex-cuyahoga county judge is accused of killing his ex wife,  aisha fraser mason.  a prior domestic abuse case from 2014 shows that lance mason had a history of violence against fraser mason, a sixth grade teacher who he shared two children with. at that time, fraser mason was forced to undergo reconstructive surgery for her injuries, according to cleveland.com. 
mason was sentenced to only two years in prison in that domestic abuse case. he was released after only nine months and a written apology to his estranged wife who filed for divorce after the 2014 domestic abuse occurrence. although mason lost his ability to sit on the bench, he was hired as a minority business development director.  #rip aisha fraser mason
#enddomesticviolence #weareinthistogether #metoo #victim

„Éª„Éª„Éª
‚Äú6 years ago... i was wrapped in a web where everything i saw was a complete blur. i lost who i was and where i came from. i obsessed over your attention and so called ‚Äúlove‚Äù i gave you every once of me...every fucking inch. i remember the day i realized my life was no longer my life. i remember you as someone who degraded me. you made me vanish without me knowing. i was know longer apart of this world. i was apart of your world and what you believed. i was only allowed to listen to what you said. i was only allowed to show my skin, my hair when it was just you and i. i changed everything i knew for you. i didn‚Äôt have time to question what was right and what was wrong. all i can remember was ur hands against my face telling me i was a bitch. i was your bitch. and i had no other option but to obey what you said. i cried days upon days. nights became darker and darker. your hands fit perfect against my cheek bones. you sure knew how to beg me to stop. you are the ugliest part of my past. and thankful you no longer have control of who i am. 
i can‚Äôt stop being thankful for knowing i was able to escape something that still haunts me today. something that was so brainwashing, something that destroyed me for so long. never loose hope and never let anyone take control of who are. mental and physical abuse is much more than just walking away. it‚Äôs easier said than done. and i want anyone who is going through such a horrific cycle to know that you are loved and that you to can escape it. find your strength.‚Äù
#weareinthistogether #enddomesticviolence #metoo #survivor

text:
regret is not a good companion :: they say the only things we truly wind up regretting are the chances we never take; the things we never do; the people we never risked loving; the turns we never completed.
.
that use to be me. i allowed my fears, my doubts and often my analysis keep me from even attempting to make changes. (can you say analysis paralysis!!!
.
i was so afraid of the outcome being negative that it literally stopped me from even taking a chance that something could turn out positive.
.
that is, until i said enough is enough on april 10, 2017, my no, not now turned into yes, it‚Äôs time and it changed everything!
.
now i‚Äôm on the other side of that yes. now i get to talk with so many others who are now where i was (maybe it was you)! now i get to give them hope and cheer them on when they finally choose their yes!! my heart also breaks when i hear their stories and then hear their no, not now.
.
will everything work for everybody, no of course not?! but that‚Äôs exactly why i believe in what i‚Äôm doing so much üíõ: it‚Äôs not a one size fits all. i‚Äôve lost -183 lbs at 45 years old and in 19 months because i learned how to stop dieting and start living. it‚Äôs principles ~ it‚Äôs a mindset. by practicing them with healthy accountability and support i figured out exactly what works for me and you can do the same thing. it‚Äôs really not rocket science and it‚Äôs definitely not hard.
.
it‚Äôs simple. it‚Äôs sensible. it‚Äôs sustainable.
.
yes, i can share the mindset, the tools and resources. yes i can offer support and encouragement. yes i can connect you with a network of women all working together positivity to do it too but you have to choose to say yes!!
=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=‚Ä¢=
if today is your day? if you finally want to drop the excuses and stop the regret üëÜclick the [start here] link in my bio and i‚Äôll help you get started. üíõ

text:
a #waybackwednesday letter to my kid-self.

little one,

i see you drowning. you have gone through so much in your short time on this earth. your innocence ripped from you like an old bandaid. discarded...your developing mind and body still trying to comprehend it all. you feel alone and many times you are. walking on eggshells and covering up your shame and hurt like a heavy silent burden. every once in a while you lock yourself up in the bathroom distraught, when you should be playing carefree. toxic thoughts poisoning your young mind. you are scared but you have fight in you, although you might not realize this yet. there are still many battles to come and your truth will be scattered around like a puzzle that seems unsolvable. but i promise you will find all the pieces and make them fit. you'll do many great things one day kiddo. you may never fully stop doubting yourself but every year you'll be a little kinder to yourself. spread your truth and help others find their voice in a world that tries to silence or shame them.

#survivor #warriorwoman #alettertomyself #werisebyliftingothers #metoo #ibelievesurvivors #useyourvoice #aperfect14 #strenght #kerosenedeluxe #healing #empowered #vixennotavictim

text:
#metoo ‚Äì reflections
.
nowadays, intersectionality can sometimes be used as a buzzword, a badge of honour that legitimises your feminist politics as woke and acceptable. but what does intersectionality really mean when it comes to feminism? although the topic is vast, we‚Äôll start to touch on some of the ideas here.
.
civil rights activist and law professor, kimberl√© williams crenshaw, originally coined the term intersectionality within a legal context, almost thirty years ago.  the term was used to explain how anti-discrimination law treated gender and race as separate issues. this compounded and allowed for systematic oppression against african-american women, particularly in legal contexts.
.
summarising the concept, professor crenshaw describes it, as ‚Äúa metaphor, for understanding the ways in which multiple forms of inequality or disadvantage sometimes compound themselves and they create obstacles that often are not understood within conventional ways of thinking about anti-racism, or feminism or whatever social justice advocacy structures we have.‚Äù
.
intersectionality is a lens through which you can see where power comes and collides, where it interlocks and intersects. it‚Äôs not simply that there‚Äôs a race problem here, a gender problem here, and a class or lbgtq problem there. many times that framework erases what happens to people who are subject to all of these things.‚Äù
.
this term has quite recently seen a rise in popularity. but, as crenshaw and many black feminists have pointed out, this work has been carried out by women of colour for a very long time.
.
do you think intersectionality was embraced, realised or understood in the #metoo movement? we‚Äôd love to hear your thoughts.
.
@kimberlecrenshaw .
.
.
.
.
.

the driving ban was lifted early this year thanks to loujain & other activists. but soon after, saudi authorities arrested her at her home. 
loujain has now been in prison for 7 months. 
the government launched a smear campaign against her, calling her a 'traitor' & 'enemy of the state'. @amnesty reported she & other activists are being tortured & sexually harassed.

at #oyw2018, the founders called for global support to set loujain & the other activists free.

text:
this was taken in the fall of 2016, i was trying to moderate or control my drinking and thought i would be successful. 
i have been able to do pretty much everything i have set out to accomplish in my life that i focused on an worked for , i was able to get good grades, land the ta position i wanted in grad school after being rejected the first time, get the job i wanted at a big 4 firm, accomplished my goals for working abroad and creating the opportunities that sent me to hawaii, australia and singapore üå∫ i have been recruited from every position into something new and exciting and my technical skills plus curiosity and willingness to work hard have allowed me to create a wonderful life for myself. i figured sobriety would be easier than all the effort i have put into building my career but i was wrong! i don't say this to brag but to let you know more about me, i am a hard working tax software nerd. not that glamorous!
quitting drinking was something my younger brother was able to do, i had heard speakers like @richroll and @glennondoyle speak about sobriety and i felt if they could do it i certainly should be able to also. 
however it really isn't that easy and takes far more than i knew at the time. it's a daily decision to say no thanks, think about the long term consequences and choose not to escape. drinking is the easiest way to escape reality, it's fast, cheap and readily available. 
i wasn't able to stop drinking until feb of the following year, change takes time so don't beat yourself up if you drink this holiday season. one day you will find the strength you never knew you had! üí™

i always knew alcohol was bad for me but it's so social and popular i never fully comprehended the damage i was doing. it took me twenty years to stop the cycle of binge drinking and overeating. i was able to hide it during all those years i appeared to be successful on the outside.
